I. Which famous female cryptanalyst helped lay early groundwork for U.S. codebreaking before and during WWII?
A) Virginia Dare Aderholdt
B) Agnes Meyer Driscoll
C) Helen Nibouar

Hint: What is the Detective’s name?
Answer: B) Agnes Meyer Driscoll


II. What was one of the key breakthroughs achieved by Genevieve Grotjan Feinstein?
A) Designing the Enigma machine
B) Identifying patterns that helped crack the Japanese “Purple” cipher
C) Inventing radar technology 

Hint: What is the Hacker’s name?
Answer: B) Identifying patterns that helped crack the Japanese “Purple” cipher



III. What nickname is commonly used for the group of women codebreakers in the U.S. Navy and Army during WWII?
A) The Cipher Sisters
B) The Code Girls
C) The Signal Maidens 

Hint: What does C.G. in the Museum’s name stand for?

Answer: B) The Code Girls

IV. Many Code Girls were recruited directly from college campuses primarily because they had studied what subject area?
A) Mathematics and modern languages
B) Engineering and chemistry
C) Political science and history

Hint: “Mathematics is the language with which God has written the universe.” – Galileo Galilei.
Answer: A) Mathematics and modern languages

V. What was the primary function of the Code Girls during WWII?
A) Translating intercepted enemy diplomatic messages
B) Operating radio transmission stations in the Pacific
C) Performing cryptanalysis on encrypted naval communications
Hint: Traditionally, a military has three forces: i) The Land Force (Army); ii) The Naval Force (Navy); iii) The Air Force.
Answer: C) Performing cryptanalysis on encrypted naval communications 





